 This is a straightforward problem. We first note that the number \(10^{51} - 9\) is a 51-digit number where all the digits except the first are 9's. For example, \(10^4 - 9 = 1000 - 9 = 999\). Similarly, \(10^{51} - 9\) will be a number with 50 nines followed by a one. So, the number looks like ...

\begin{align*}
&0 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 000 001
\end{align*}

From this representation, it's clear that the sum of the digits is \(9 \times 50 + 1 = 451\). \end{think}

